04313nam a22006375i 9780824890056DE-B159720220110023848.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220110t20212022hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021009508  a97808248900567 a10.1515/97808248900562doi  a(DE-B1597)585126  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI00aBQ680.M6bM64 2021 4aBQ680.M6 7aREL0070102bisacsh04a294.30952qLOC1 aMoerman, D. Max, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Japanese Buddhist World Map :bReligious Vision and the Cartographic Imagination /cD. Max Moerman. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b146 color, b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom the fourteenth through the nineteenth centuries Japanese monks created hundreds of maps to construct and locate their place in a Buddhist world. This expansively illustrated volume is the first to explore the largely unknown archive of Japanese Buddhist world maps and analyze their production, reproduction, and reception. In examining these fascinating sources of visual and material culture, author D. Max Moerman argues for an alternative history of Japanese Buddhism—one that compels us to recognize the role of the Buddhist geographic imaginary in a culture that encompassed multiple cartographic and cosmological world views. The contents and contexts of Japanese Buddhist world maps reveal the ambivalent and shifting position of Japan in the Buddhist world, its encounter and negotiation with foreign ideas and technologies, and the possibilities for a global history of Buddhism and science. Moerman’s visual and intellectual history traces the multiple trajectories of Japanese Buddhist world maps, beginning with the earliest extant Japanese map of the world: a painting by a fourteenth-century Japanese monk charting the cosmology and geography of India and Central Asia based on an account written by a seventh-century Chinese pilgrim-monk. He goes on to discuss the cartographic inclusion and marginal position of Japan, the culture of the copy and the power of replication in Japanese Buddhism, and the transcultural processes of engagement and response to new visions of the world produced by Iberian Christians, Chinese Buddhists, and the Japanese maritime trade. Later chapters explore the transformations in the media and messages of Buddhist cartography in the age of print culture and in intellectual debates during the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries over cosmology and epistemology and the polemics of Buddhist science.The Japanese Buddhist World Map offers a wholly innovative picture of Japanese Buddhism that acknowledges the possibility of multiple and heterogeneous modernities and alternative visions of Japan and the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 0aBuddhismzJapanxMaps. 0aBuddhist cosmology. 0aBuddhist geography. 0aCartographyzJapanxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / History.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780824890056zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824890056423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824890056/original  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK